    <p>To stop the bladder from continuing to scar, you need to stop the cause: the obstruction and inflammation that are forcing it to overwork.</p>

    <p>Two things need to happen simultaneously.</p>

    <p>First, the hormonal driver of prostate growth needs to be addressed. DHT — the hormone converted from testosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha-reductase — is the primary signal telling the prostate to keep enlarging. Block that enzyme, and you cut off the fuel.</p>

    <p>Second, the active inflammation in the prostate tissue needs to be reduced — because inflammation is what causes the prostate to swell against the urethra in the first place. And the smooth muscle around the urethra and bladder neck needs to relax the tension it's been holding, so the obstruction can physically open.</p>

    <p>When both happen together, the pressure on the bladder drops. The straining stops. And the tissue that's still recoverable gets the chance to do so.</p>

    <p>This is the core of what I call the Pelvic Decompression approach — and it's the combination of ingredients I've recommended to patients for years who want to address this proactively, before the window closes.</p>

